Project Overview

This project demonstrates how to host a static website on AWS S3 and enhance its performance and security using CloudFront CDN.

The website is stored in an S3 bucket and delivered globally through CloudFront with HTTPS support.

🏗️ Architecture
Static website hosted in S3
CloudFront used as CDN for faster delivery
HTTPS enabled via CloudFront
Public access managed using bucket policy
🛠️ Implementation Steps
🔹 1. Create S3 Bucket
Created S3 bucket with globally unique name
Disabled Block Public Access
Uploaded website files (index.html)
🔹 2. Enable Static Website Hosting
Enabled static website hosting in bucket properties
Set:
Index document: index.html
🔹 3. Configure Bucket Policy

Allowed public read access:

{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "PublicRead",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": ["s3:GetObject"],
      "Resource": ["arn:aws:s3:::my-static-website-17-04/*"]
    }
  ]
}
🔹 4. Test S3 Website

Accessed via:

http://my-static-website-17-04.s3-website-ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/
🔹 5. Create CloudFront Distribution
Origin: S3 website endpoint
Viewer protocol policy: Redirect HTTP → HTTPS
Default root object: index.html
🔹 6. Access via CloudFront

Final website URL:

https://d3g8xfbic543k9.cloudfront.net/
🧪 Challenges Faced & Solutions
❌ Issue: Access Denied from S3

Cause:

Used incorrect S3 endpoint

Fix:

Enabled static website hosting
Used correct website endpoint
❌ Issue: CloudFront “Failed to contact origin”

Cause:

Used S3 REST endpoint instead of website endpoint
Protocol mismatch (HTTPS vs HTTP)

Fix:

Changed origin to S3 website endpoint
Set origin protocol to HTTP
💰 Cost Estimate
S3: Minimal (free tier eligible)
CloudFront: ₹5–₹20 for testing
🧹 Cleanup

To avoid charges:

Delete CloudFront distribution
Delete S3 bucket
🎯 Key Learnings
Hosted static website using S3
Used CloudFront CDN for global content delivery
Understood difference between S3 REST endpoint and website endpoint
Debugged real-world CloudFront origin issues

Challenges Faced
- Faced AccessDenied error due to using incorrect S3 endpoint
- Fixed by enabling static website hosting and updating bucket policy
- Encountered CloudFront origin error due to using S3 REST endpoint
- Resolved by switching to S3 website endpoint and setting origin protocol to HTTP
